1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3
d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d4 {There was a long time when
White could not find anything against the Marshall Attack. The situation is
about to change and lately Black has lost quite a few games at teh top level.}
Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 15. Be3 Bg4 16. Qd3 Rae8 17. Nd2 {Almost in any
opening, what we use to call "the old main line" is the one which, objectively,
offers the best chances for White, although fashion rarely has anything to do
with it.} Qh5 {A rare move, which Leko had tried in practice before.} ({"The
old main line" goes} 17... Re6 {Lately, there have been some interesting
developments after} 18. Qf1 $5 Qh5 19. f3 Nxe3 20. Qf2 Nd5 21. fxg4 Qxg4 22.
Qf3 $5 Qxf3 (22... Qg5 {Kramnik,V (2772)-Aronian,L (2759)/Yerevan 2007/CBM 118/
[Marin,M] (1-0, 45)}) 23. Nxf3 h6 $5 (23... Rfe8 {was my recommendation in the
notes to the aforementioned game}) 24. Rxe6 fxe6 25. Nd2 a5 26. a4 ({It may
have been better to maintain the tension with} 26. a3 $5 $14 b4 $140 $2 27.
axb4 axb4 28. c4 Nc7 29. Ra7 $16) 26... b4 27. c4 Nc7 28. Bc2 (28. c5 $5) 28...
c5 29. Ne4 Rd8 30. Nxc5 Bxc5 31. dxc5 Rd4 32. b3 Na6 33. c6 Kf7 $44 {and White
could not break Black's dark-squared blockade in Naiditsch,A (2665)-Ivanisevic,
I (2664)/Subotica 2008 (1/2-1/2, 50)}) 18. Bc2 $5 {An interesting idea.
Usually, White keeps the bishop on b3, in order to neutralize the d5-knight.
However, the last few years have shown that Marshall Attack players know how
to defend positions in which they enjoy stability on light squares (as would
be the case of an eventual exchange on d5, even if White retains the extra
pawn).} ({Here is a typical example:} 18. Qf1 Re7 $5 19. a4 Rfe8 20. Bxd5 Qxd5
21. axb5 axb5 22. Bf4 $5 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Rxe1 24. Qxe1 Bf8 25. Qe4 f6 26. Qxd5+
cxd5 {and White did not try too hard to win this ending in Anand,V (2786)-Leko,
P (2738)/Dortmund 2007/CBM 119/[Marin,M] (1/2-1/2, 29)}) 18... f5 19. f3 Bxf3 {
However, Black has faced constant problems in positions where the b3-bishop
has no counterpart. This was the case in the games quoted in the notes to the
17th move and this will be the case in the curent game. Probably, a different
approach is needed to defend such "just slightly" worse endings, something
that has to be discovered yet. Or maybe there is no 100% proof solution for
Black and this is the kind of positions White should be aiming for. The future
will tell.} ({Less than two weeks after his win over Leko, Ponomariov faced a
novelty from a much lower rated player:} 19... Bh3 20. Bf2 Qg6 21. Rxe8 Rxe8
22. Re1 Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 h5 $44 24. Bb3 Kh7 25. Bf2 Nf4 26. Qe3 h4 27. Nf1 Nd5
28. Qd3 Nf4 29. Qe3 Nd5 30. Qd3 Nf4 31. Qe3 {1/2-1/2 Ponomariov,R (2718)
-Gustafsson,J (2620)/Cala Mayor 2008}) 20. Nxf3 Qxf3 21. Bd2 $1 Qxd3 ({Black
could avoid the exchange of queens only at the cost of losing activity:} 21...
Qh5 22. Rxe8 Qxe8 23. a4 $14) 22. Bxd3 f4 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Kf2 $14 {White's
pair of bishops offer him a long term advantage. Confronted with an unpleasant
psychological situation, Leko will go down rather painfully.} fxg3+ (24... c5
$5 25. c4 $140 Ne3 $5) 25. hxg3 c5 26. c4 Nb6 27. cxb5 c4 28. Bf1 axb5 29. Bg2
Rf8+ 30. Bf3 Be7 31. Ba5 Na4 $6 (31... Nd5 32. a3 Bd8 33. Bxd8 Rxd8 34. Re1 Nf6
35. Re5 Rb8 (35... Rxd4 36. Rxb5 $14) 36. Rc5 $14) 32. b3 Bf6 33. Kg2 $1 $16
Bxd4 $2 34. Rf1 $1 Rxf3 35. Rxf3 Nb2 36. Rf5 c3 37. Rxb5 c2 38. Rb8+ Kf7 39.
